│                                                                                            │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                            │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The crash occurs at `InstructionsState::valid()` which is called from                      │
│ `TreeEntry::hasState()`. The debugger indicates that the `this` pointer for the            │
│ `InstructionsState` object is invalid (`0x1b8`), causing a segmentation fault when we try  │
│ to access its members. This invalid pointer is held within a                               │
│ `std::unique_ptr<InstructionsState> State` member of a `BoUpSLP::TreeEntry` object.        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The call stack leads us to `BoUpSLP::computeMinimumValueSizes`, which is iterating over    │
│ the users of a `TreeEntry`. The crash happens when checking the state of one of these user │
│ `TreeEntry`s. This suggests that we have a `TreeEntry` in our graph that has a corrupted   │
│ `State` unique_ptr.                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `SLP` debug log is quite revealing. It shows the bottom-up construction of the         │
│ vectorization tree. Let's trace the creation of the `TreeEntry` objects:                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ 1.  `SLP: added a new TreeEntry (CastInst).` (ID 0, for the `sext` instructions)           │
│ 2.  `SLP: added a new TreeEntry (CmpInst).` (ID 1, for the `icmp` instructions)            │
│ 3.  `SLP: added a new TreeEntry (strided LoadInst).` (ID 4, for the first set of loads)    │
│ 4.  `SLP: added a new TreeEntry (non-consecutive LoadInst).` (ID 5, for the second set of  │
│ loads)                                                                                     │
│ 5.  `SLP: added a new TreeEntry (GetElementPtrInst).` (ID 6, for the `getelementptr`       │
│ instructions)                                                                              │
│ 6.  `SLP: added a new TreeEntry (SelectInst/...).` (ID 8, for the `select` instructions)   │
│ 7.  `SLP: added a new TreeEntry (CastInst).` (ID 9, for the `trunc` instructions)          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The log also shows "Perfect diamond merge" messages. This happens when the vectorizer      │
│ identifies a node that is reachable through multiple paths in the dependency graph.        │
│ Specifically, we see:                                                                      │
│ *   `SLP: Perfect diamond merge at %26 = load ...`                                         │
│ *   `SLP: Perfect diamond merge at %26 = load ...`                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ This indicates that the `TreeEntry` for the strided loads (ID 4) is being reused. The      │
│ `BoUpSLP::getTreeEntry` function handles this by returning the existing entry.             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problem arises when we build the tree. The `trunc` instructions (which form            │
│ `TreeEntry` 9) use the strided loads (from `TreeEntry` 4). The `select` instructions (in   │
│ `TreeEntry` 8) also use the `trunc` instructions. The `getelementptr` instructions (in     │
│ `TreeEntry` 6) use the `select` instructions. Finally, the gather loads (in `TreeEntry` 5) │
│ use the `getelementptr` instructions.                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ This creates a dependency chain: `Gather Loads (5) -> GEPs (6) -> Selects (8) -> Truncs    │
│ (9) -> Strided Loads (4)`.                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ However, the `icmp` instructions (in `TreeEntry` 1) also depend on both the strided loads  │
│ (`TreeEntry` 4) and the gather loads (`TreeEntry` 5). This creates a complex graph with    │
│ multiple paths to the same node.                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause lies in how `BoUpSLP` handles graph construction and state management,      │
│ particularly with diamond-shaped dependencies.                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ When a `TreeEntry` is created, its `State` is initialized. When we build the tree upwards, │
│ we link entries together by adding `EdgeInfo` to the `Users` list of an operand            │
│ `TreeEntry`.                                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The crash happens in `computeMinimumValueSizes`, which is called during horizontal         │
│ reduction analysis. This function iterates through the `Users` of a `TreeEntry`. In our    │
│ case, it's likely iterating through the users of the `TreeEntry` for the strided loads (ID │
│ 4).                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ One of its users is the `trunc` instructions (`TreeEntry` 9). Another user is the `icmp`   │
│ instructions (`TreeEntry` 1). The `icmp` instructions also use the gather loads            │
│ (`TreeEntry` 5), which themselves depend on the strided loads through a chain of other     │
│ instructions.                                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The key issue is that during the complex graph construction, a `TreeEntry`'s `State`       │
│ unique_ptr is being moved from, leaving it in a null state. Later, when another part of    │
│ the code tries to add a user to this same `TreeEntry`, it sees the null `State` and        │
│ attempts to re-initialize it. However, instead of a proper re-initialization, it seems a   │
│ stale or incorrect value is being used, leading to the `State` pointer holding the garbage │
│ value `0x1b8`.                                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The function `BoUpSLP::buildTree` has logic to handle such scenarios. When it finds an     │
│ existing `TreeEntry`, it's supposed to correctly link it into the graph. The bug is that   │
│ this linking process is flawed when a node is revisited through a different path in the    │
│ graph, causing the `State` to be improperly handled and corrupted.                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ Specifically, when `getTreeEntry` is called for the same set of scalars, it returns the    │
│ existing `TreeEntry`. If this entry's state was already moved out (e.g., during the        │
│ processing of another user), we have a problem. The code should ensure that a              │
│ `TreeEntry`'s state is valid before adding new users or operating on it.                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure that when we retrieve an existing `TreeEntry` via `getTreeEntry`, we  │
│ also restore its `State` if it has been moved. This can be done by passing the `State`     │
│ unique_ptr to `getTreeEntry` and having it move the state into the `TreeEntry` if the      │
│ entry already exists but its state is null.                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix involves modifying `BoUpSLP::getTreeEntry` to handle the state restoration and     │
│ updating its call sites.                                                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ **File:** `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ **Edit 1: Modify `getTreeEntry` function signature and implementation.**                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp:18018                                   │
│ BoUpSLP::TreeEntry *BoUpSLP::getTreeEntry(ArrayRef<Value *> VL,                            │
│                                          std::unique_ptr<InstructionsState> &S,            │
│                                          const APInt &Demanded) {                          │
│   // Sort the scalars to canonicalize the list.                                            │
│   SmallVector<Value *, 4> SortedVL(VL.begin(), VL.end());                                  │
│   llvm::sort(SortedVL, [](Value *A, Value *B) { return A->hasName() && B->hasName() &&     │
│ A->getName() < B->getName(); });                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│   // Check if we have it already.                                                          │
│   auto I = ScalarToTreeEntry.find(SortedVL);                                               │
│   if (I != ScalarToTreeEntry.end()) {                                                      │
│     // If the entry is empty, we are building a new entry with the same scalars            │
│     // as some other entry.                                                                │
│     if (!I->second->State)                                                                 │
│       I->second->State = std::move(S);                                                     │
│     return I->second;                                                                      │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ **Edit 2: Update the call site in `buildTree_rec`.**                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp:18180                                   │
│   // Sort the scalars to canonicalize the list.                                            │
│   if (MustStartNewTree) {                                                                  │
│     Entry = getTreeEntry(VL, S, Demanded);                                                 │
│   } else {                                                                                 │
│     if (Entry) {                                                                           │
│       // We are reusing an existing entry. Make sure it has a state.                       │
│       if (!Entry->State)                                                                   │
│         Entry->State = std::move(S);                                                       │
│     } else {                                                                               │
│       Entry = getTreeEntry(VL, S, Demanded);                                               │
│     }                                                                                      │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ **Edit 3: Update the other call site in `buildTree`.**                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp:18260                                   │
│   // We have a good candidate.                                                             │
│   std::unique_ptr<InstructionsState> S =                                                   │
│       std::make_unique<InstructionsState>(VL, Shuffle, this, Demanded);                    │
│   BoUpSLP::TreeEntry *E = getTreeEntry(VL, S, Demanded);                                   │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The crash was caused by a state corruption issue within the `BoUpSLP` tree construction    │
│ logic. When dealing with complex, diamond-shaped dependency graphs, a `TreeEntry`'s        │
│ `State` unique_ptr could be moved, leaving it null. Subsequent attempts to use this        │
│ `TreeEntry` would lead to incorrect re-initialization and ultimately a crash.              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The proposed fix addresses this by modifying `getTreeEntry` to take ownership of the       │
│ `State` unique_ptr and restore it to an existing `TreeEntry` if its state has been moved.  │
│ This ensures that all `TreeEntry` objects in the graph maintain a valid state, preventing  │
│ the crash and allowing the vectorizer to correctly analyze and transform the code.         │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
