│ However, the core logic described in the root cause analysis remains valid: a              │
│ `TreeEntry`'s state is being corrupted when a node in the SLP graph is revisited. The      │
│ analysis points to a "get-or-create" function for `TreeEntry` objects as the place for the │
│ fix.                                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ Based on my exploration of the code, the function `BoUpSLP::buildTree_rec` handles the     │
│ recursive construction of the tree. Inside this function, there's logic to detect when a   │
│ set of scalars (`VL`) has already been processed and added to the tree. This is the        │
│ "diamond merge" point mentioned in the analysis.                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // from llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                    │
│ // ... inside buildTree_rec ...                                                            │
│   if (S) {                                                                                 │
│     LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SLP: \tChecking bundle: " << *S.getMainOp() << ".\n");           │
│     for (TreeEntry *E : getTreeEntries(S.getMainOp())) {                                   │
│       if (E->isSame(VL)) {                                                                 │
│         // Record the reuse of the tree node.                                              │
│         E->UserTreeIndices.push_back(UserTreeIdx);                                         │
│         LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SLP: Perfect diamond merge at " << *S.getMainOp()            │
│                           << ".\n");                                                       │
│         return;                                                                            │
│       }                                                                                    │
│ // ...                                                                                     │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ When a pre-existing `TreeEntry` `E` is found, the code simply adds the new user and        │
│ returns. However, it doesn't check if `E->State` is valid. If the state was moved out      │
│ during the processing of a previous user, `E->State` could be null, leading to the crash   │
│ later on.                                                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure the `TreeEntry` has a valid state when it's being reused. The         │
│ `InstructionsState` `S` for the current set of scalars (`VL`) has already been computed.   │
│ If the existing `TreeEntry` `E` has no state, we can simply move `S` into it.              │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply this fix.                                                                 │
